'''Mark T. Sullivan''' (b. 1958)<ref name=locrec>[http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no95000558.html LOC record for Mark T. Sullivan]</ref> is an American author who writes mystery, suspense and historical fiction novels. His fourteen published works that are written solely by him include ''The Fall Line,'' ''The Purification Ceremony'', ''Triple Cross'', ''Rogue'' and the ''USA Today''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2013/06/21/beneath-a-scarlet-sky/2444877/isbn/9781503943377/|title=Beneath a Scarlet Sky|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref> ''and Washington Post''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/books/best-sellers/2018/01/28/national-fiction/|title=Bestsellers: National Fiction|last=|first=|date=January 28, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> bestselling novel, Beneath a Scarlet Sky.
He has also written, as of June 2016, five novels with [[James Patterson]].<ref>James Patterson website, at http://www.jamespatterson.com/books.php#.VG2Xq8J0zIU .</ref>

== Biography and career ==

Sullivan was born and raised in [[Medfield, Massachusetts]], a suburb of [[Boston]].<ref>[http://marksullivanbooks.com/?page_id=12 About Mark] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002005741/http://marksullivanbooks.com/?page_id=12 |date=2012-10-02 }} Accessed 1 June 2012.</ref> He earned a BA in English from [[Hamilton College (New York)|Hamilton College]] in 1980. After graduating, he served as a volunteer in the [[Peace Corps]], teaching English to children of [[Tuareg people|Tuareg]] nomads in the Sahara Desert.

Sullivan returned to the United States in 1982 and studied at the [[Medill School of Journalism]] of [[Northwestern University]] in Evanston, Illinois.

He began writing fiction at 30 and his first novel, ''The Fall Line'' (1994), was a ''New York Times'' Notable Book of the Year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/04/books/notable-books-of-the-year-1994.html|title=Notable Books of the Year: 1994|date=1994-12-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

His 2017 novel, ''Beneath a Scarlet Sky,'' was optioned in 2017 by Pascal Pictures with actor [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]] attached to star in the lead role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/tom-holland-amy-pascal-pino-lello-beneath-a-scarlet-sky-spiderman-homecoming-1202148294/|title=Pascal Pictures Lands ‘Beneath A Scarlet Sky’ For Tom Holland|last=Jr|first=Mike Fleming|last2=Jr|first2=Mike Fleming|date=2017-08-15|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref>

